      <hedline>
        <hl1>West Side Garbage Plan</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Matthew Washington letter notes that many civic organizations and elected officials have proposed alternatives to New York City's plan to use Hudson River Park as its new garbage holding area</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Hard-Won Garbage Plan Runs Into Trouble in Albany'' (news article, June 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Hard-Won Garbage Plan Runs Into Trouble in Albany'' (news article, June 1):</p>
        <p>Many civic organizations and elected officials have joined together to propose alternatives to New York City's plan to use Hudson River Park as its new garbage holding area.</p>
        <p>Contrary to Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg's statement that the Gansevoort Peninsula is the only viable option, there is a lot of support for alternative sites in the West 30s and 40s.</p>
        <p>The two major alternatives are Pier 76 -- the Police Tow Pound, which state law requires be moved off the pier anyway -- and a rail-based waste transfer station using the Empire Line track that runs right along the mid-West Side of Manhattan.</p>
        <p>The sites we've proposed can be built within reasonable budget ceilings, would handle more waste than the proposed Hudson River Park sites, can be completed sooner and have the additional and considerable advantage that they are legal.</p>
        <p>This kind of response to a government proposal is not Nimbyism. It is an effort to participate in the decisions our government makes about our neighborhoods.</p>
        <p>Matthew Washington  Deputy Director  Friends of Hudson River Park  New York, June 5, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
